      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i get the vibe you're going for with the \"magical bond\" thing, but i need to be a bit more specific for the exam. i keep seeing the phrase \"spooky action at a distance\" in my textbook. what exactly is meant by that? why is it considered \"spooky\" instead of just being a normal part of how things work?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the phrase \"spooky action at a distance,\" coined by Albert Einstein himself, refers to the peculiar and seemingly magical phenomenon of quantum entanglement. It's considered \"spooky\" because it defies our everyday experiences and intuition. In the classical world, we expect that objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings. So, if you have two entangled particles, like two magical orbs, and you move one orb to a distant planet, we wouldn't expect the other orb to instantly change its state, even though they're separated by vast distances.\n\nBut in the quantum world, when you entangle two particles, their states become linked, no matter how far apart they are. So, if you change the state of one particle, the other particle's state changes instantly, as if they were connected by an invisible, magical thread. This instantaneous change happens faster than the speed of light, which is why Einstein called it \"spooky.\" It's like having a secret, unbreakable connection with your friend that lets you know their every move, no matter how far apart you are. And that's why it's considered \"spooky\" instead of just being a normal part of how things work. It's a strange and mysterious part of the quantum world that",
      "source": "target",
